<p></p>.<p>A lack of facial expressions can occur in various conditions. <i><a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/catatonia_catatonic_behavior/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Catatonia</a></i> is a term that is used to describe a state of stupor or unresponsiveness in a person who is otherwise awake.  Lack of facial expressions is one sign of catatonia, which can occur in association with a psychiatric disorder, like <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/schizophrenia/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">schizophrenia</a>. Diseases that cause damage to the brain and its function can also lead to a lack of responsiveness, including a lack of facial expressions. Examples include brain <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/trauma_and_first_aid_quiz/quiz.htm" rel="quiz" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">trauma</a> and 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/encephalitis_and_meningitis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">encephalitis</a>.</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>